<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-435-367  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 435 367.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Reseller News  Sept 17 1990 n386 p3(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Windows goes upscale; IBM support could mean a standard graphicalenvironment.(Microsoft may make Windows its standard graphicaluser interface for workstations and limit OS/2 to network servers)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Dodge, John M.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Sources at the NetWorld trade show in early Sep 1990 indicate thatMicrosoft Corp may establish Windows as its long-term workstationgraphical user interface and limit OS/2 development to networkservers.andP;  Sources inside and outside Microsoft claim the change isbeing considered as a result of Windows' popularity and therejection of OS/2, which analysts say now trails both DOS andWindows.andP;  A Microsoft source says a joint IBM-Microsoftannouncement intended to end confusion on Windows and OS/2 isimminent; a previous joint announcement by the companies at ComdexFall 1989 only confused users.andP;  At that time IBM announced itsintention to develop a 2Mbyte version of OS/2, which Microsoftofficials did not like; the resulting OS/2 1.3 is the best versionof the operating system so far, however.andP;  The trend toward Windowsand away from OS/2 and IBM's plans in the area are discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (product development)Microsoft Corp. (product development).andO;Ticker:    MSFT; IBM.andO;Topic:     Graphical User InterfaceSoftware SelectionProduct DevelopmentPlanningMarket AnalysisSoftware PublishersOS-2MS-DOS.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>